\begin_layout Subsection
Winding number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Associated to each sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a winding number 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega=\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{x_{n}}{n}
\]

\end_inset

This is illustrated in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Winding-number"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The winding number is, in general, well-defined, since, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x_{n+1}-x_{n}\right|\le\left|\omega\right|+\left|K\right|\le2$
\end_inset

, at least when limited to the region 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\omega,K\le1$
\end_inset

, as is usually the case for these images.
 Thus, on first priciples, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n}\le\left|x_{n}\right|\le\sum_{k=0}^{n-1}\left|x_{n+1}-x_{n}\right|\le n\left(\left|\omega\right|+\left|K\right|\right)
\]

\end_inset

from which one deduces
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\le\Omega\le\left|\omega\right|+\left|K\right|
\]

\end_inset

Experimentally, it appears that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\le\Omega\le1
\]

\end_inset

almost always.
\end_layout

