\begin_layout Subsection
Poincare recurrence time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often the case that the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}\right\} $
\end_inset

 will settle down to asymptotically periodic orbits as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 At least, it does so, except when it doesn't: some orbits remain chaotic.
 Much of the rest of this paper is an exploration as to how to correctly
 eistinguish these two regimes.
 One classic technique is to experimentally determine the Poincare recurrence
 time.
 This is defined as the smallest number of iterations 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 such that, for sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|x_{n+\tau}-x_{n}\right|<\epsilon
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 That is, a given orbit returns 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

close enough
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to a point that was visited before.
 This is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Poincare-recurrence-time"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general appearance of the image does not depend on the specific value
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

, as long as it is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not too small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This is because it can take a long time for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 to settle into a periodic orbit; thus, if one attempts to measure the recurrenc
e time before the orbit has settled, one will have poor measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement technique used in this figure was to pre-iterate 
\begin_inset Formula $n=90$
\end_inset

 times, and then use 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}=x_{90}$
\end_inset

 as the initial starting point.
 Iteration continued for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 more steps, until 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x_{90+\tau}-x_{90}\right|<\epsilon$
\end_inset

 was satisfied.
 To get a better approximation, iteration continued for 500 more steps,
 and an average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 was taken.
 The figure shows no particularly visible dependence on the starting point
 (the 
\begin_inset Formula $n=90$
\end_inset

 point), on the extended number of iterations, or on the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 There is, presumably, some dependence, but this is not characterized.
 There is a strong dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and so, to get well-behaved values, the recurance time (for each pixel)
 is averaged over hundreds of different randomly selected 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 values.
 Close examination of the image reveals speckling; this speckling goes away
 as more averages per pixel are taken.
\end_layout

